Task 1 - NRI Data Cleaning

1. Import the NRI data. Ensure that the FIPS code variable (âSTCOFIPSâ) is correctly identified as a string / character variable. Otherwise, the leading zeros will be removed.

knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "..\\")
#setwd("C:\\Users\\jgluckman\\OneDrive - RAND Corporation\\Desktop\\Machine Learning\\PRGS-Intro-to-ML-2025\\")
pacman::p_load(tidyverse)
nri <- read.csv("data\\raw\\NRI_Table_Counties.csv", colClasses = "character")

2. Subset the NRI data to include only the 5-digit state/county FIPS code and all colums ending with â_AFREQâ and â_RISKRâ. Each of these columns represents a different hazard type.

sub <- nri %>% select(ends_with(c("AFREQ", "RISKR")))
sub$fips <- paste(nri$STATEFIPS, nri$COUNTYFIPS, sep = "")

3. Create a table / dataframe that, for each hazard type, shows the number of missing values in the â_AFREQâ and â_RISKRâ columns.

haz.types <- cbind.data.frame(names(sub)[names(sub) != "fips"])
names(haz.types) <- "full"
haz.types$call <- NA
haz.types$nom <- NA
for(i in 1:nrow(haz.types)){
    haz.types$call[i] <- gsub(".*_", "", haz.types$full[i])
    haz.types$nom[i] <- gsub("_.*", "", haz.types$full[i])
}
tmp.name <- which(names(nri) %in% (haz.types$full) == TRUE)
nas <- NA
for(i in tmp.name){
    nas <- c(nas, length(nri[,i][nri[,i] == ""]))
}
haz.types$count <- nas[2:length(nas)]
haz.types$full <- NULL
haz.types <- haz.types %>%
                pivot_wider(names_from = "call", values_from = "count")

4. Create a new column in the original data table indicating whether or not âAVLN_AFREQâ is missing or observed. Show the cross-tabulation of the âAVLN_AFREQâ missingness and âAVLN_RISKRâ columns (including missing values). What do you observe?

sub$aa_miss <- sub$AVLN_AFREQ == ""
avln <- cbind.data.frame(sub$aa_miss, sub$AVLN_RISKR)

When AVLN_AFREQ is missing, AVLN_RISKR is Not Applicable. 5. Assuming that a risk that is ânot applicableâ to a county has an annualized frequency of 0, impute the relevant missing values in the â_AFREQâ columns with 0.

for(i in 1:length(haz.types$nom)){
    rootname <- haz.types$nom[i]
    rost.afreq <- paste(rootname, "AFREQ", sep = "_")
    col.afreq <- which(names(sub) == rost.afreq)
    rost.riskr <- paste(rootname, "RISKR", sep = "_")
    col.riskr <- which(names(sub) == rost.riskr)
    sub[, col.afreq][sub[, col.riskr] == "Not Applicable"] <- 0
    sub[, col.afreq] <- as.numeric(sub[, col.afreq])
}

Task 3 - Data Merging

1. Identify any FIPS codes that are present in the NRI data but not in the SVI data and vice versa. Describe any discrepancies and possible causes? What to these discrepancies, if any, mean for interpreting results based on the merged dataset moving forward?

nri.only <- sub$fips[!(sub$fips %in% svi.short$FIPS)]
svi.only <- svi.short$FIPS[!(svi.short$FIPS %in% sub$fips)]

Looking at the data shows that the NRI codes include US territories like Puerto Rico, while the SVI data teases out parts of Connecticut based on an alternative schema from the FIPS codes used in the NRI data. The potential issues mean that US territories wonât be included in the final analysis, while Connecticut can only be included with some liberal interpretation choices for alternative breakdowns, which I did not do. 2. Merge the NRI and SVI data on the FIPS code. Use an outer join to keep all counties in the final dataset.

fulldat <- merge(x = sub, y = svi.short, by.x = "fips", by.y = "FIPS")
write.csv(fulldat, "data\\processed\\SVI Updated.csv")

Task 4 - Data Analysis

1. For each numerical variable in the merged dataset, plot a histogram showing the distribution of values. (Hint: write a function to make the histogram for a single variable, then use a loop or apply function to make the histograms for all numerical variables.)

frontend <- c("fips", "ST", "STATE", "ST_ABBR", "STCNTY", "COUNTY", "LOCATION", "aa_miss")
riskr <- names(fulldat)[grep("_RISKR", names(fulldat))]
afreq <- names(fulldat)[grep("_AFREQ", names(fulldat))]
ep <- names(fulldat)[grep("EP_", names(fulldat))]
fulldat <- cbind.data.frame(fulldat[frontend], fulldat[riskr], 
fulldat$AREA_SQMI, fulldat[afreq], fulldat[ep])
graphs <- list(NA)
for(i in 28:ncol(fulldat)){
    var <- names(fulldat)[i]
    loctab <- data.frame(table(fulldat[i]))
    names(loctab) <- c("val", "count")
    loctab$val <- as.numeric(loctab$val)
    loctab$count <- as.numeric(loctab$count)
    colorwheel <- c("red2", "blue3", "green4", "yellow4", "gray10")
    colorpick <- i %% length(colorwheel)
    graph <- ggplot(data = loctab) +
        geom_bar(aes(x = val, y = count), stat = "identity", 
        fill = colorwheel[colorpick]) + 
        xlim(0, max(loctab$val)) +
        ylim(0, max(loctab$count)) +
        labs(title = "Variable Histogram",
        subtitle = var,
        x = var,
        y = "Count")
    print(graph)
        graphs[[i - 27]] <- graph
        names(graphs)[i - 27] <- var
}
